Been there, done that, bought the T shirt as they say except there was no touristy T shirt to buy!  After the crazy jeep ride, the hike is fairly rigorous for the non atheletic like us city folk and there are narrow points like a small shelf which only a single person can pass through that are a bit hair raising because of the sheer drop and do get the adrenaline pumping- but its so worth it for the experience and view at the top. Due to  altitude good idea to spend a little time acclimatising if u can before you climb. But there were all ages going up and down- I went on  foot with my  7 year old daughter and 70 yrs old Dad - it took us 4+ hours going at a steady pace. There are horses available too which the locals are happy to supply as it earns them seasonal income.There are clear mountain water springs as u ascend so you can quench your thirst on the way. Once we finally reached the top we we're so exhausted we just crashed onto mattresses they put out for us! Its best to set out early morning so you get to the top sooner  and u can maximise the time exploring the meadows. It is spectacular -outta this world and Nanga Parbatt look so close up u feel u could almost touch it. Theres an option to camp a the top and meals can be freshly prepared if u give your order in advance. The meadows were so pristine , and water crystal clear and I hope it stays like that forever.

Thanks for an opportunity to feel this crazy adventure through yours experience.

Bro proppsssssss ... you guys brave enough to make it to by the jeep. We went to fairy meadows in End July 2016 by foot. It took 11hrs from raikot bridge to the view point. It was when we said we never gonna visit this place again cuz we were 5 cousins and had only 5 Ltrs of water and it was 44 C¬∞. Hope you had a clear morning view of the might Nanga Parbat. Btw in my opinion you guys should have come to Pakistan in after Mid july when the Babusar pass is open for traffic and most tourists visit. During that times the snow is also less and valleys are lush green. Plus the babusar pass roads are of international standard and no risky rides like you did from besham side. Besham side is for trucks and cargo and open in winter. Do visit Deosai Plains once in your life and Skardu when the snow is gone. Deosai is open by end july to End September and is lush green to Brown in two months. Later in Oct snows falls again. Peace
